## Problem

ChatViewModel needs to periodically check for new messages while a conversation is active.

## Solution

Add a polling coroutine that runs while conversation is active:

```kotlin
// ChatViewModel.kt
private var syncJob: Job? = null
private val syncIntervalMs = 5_000L  // 5 seconds, could be configurable

private fun startMessageSync(conversationId: String) {
    stopMessageSync()  // Cancel any existing sync

    syncJob = viewModelScope.launch {
        while (isActive) {
            delay(syncIntervalMs)

            // Only sync if still on same conversation
            if (conversationId != activeConversationId) break

            val newMessages = messageRepository.checkForNewMessages(
                agentId = agentId,
                conversationId = conversationId,
            )

            if (newMessages.isNotEmpty()) {
                // Merge into UI state
                val uiMessages = newMessages.toUiMessages()
                _uiState.update { current ->
                    current.copy(
                        messages = mergeNewMessages(current.messages, uiMessages)
                    )
                }
            }
        }
    }
}

private fun stopMessageSync() {
    syncJob?.cancel()
    syncJob = null
}

private fun mergeNewMessages(
    existing: List<UiMessage>,
    incoming: List<UiMessage>,
): ImmutableList<UiMessage> {
    val existingIds = existing.map { it.id }.toSet()
    val newOnly = incoming.filter { it.id !in existingIds }
    return (existing + newOnly).toImmutableList()
}
```

## Lifecycle Integration

- Start sync when conversation loads successfully
- Stop sync on conversation switch
- Stop sync when ViewModel cleared
- Pause when app goes to background (optional optimization)

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] `startMessageSync` and `stopMessageSync` implemented
- [ ] Polling runs every 5 seconds (configurable)
- [ ] Sync stops when conversation changes
- [ ] New messages merged without flash
- [ ] No duplicate messages in UI

## Problem

Need efficient way to check if server has messages we don't have locally.

## Solution

Add method to fetch messages after a known ID:

```kotlin
// MessageRepository.kt
suspend fun checkForNewMessages(
    agentId: String,
    conversationId: String,
): List<AppMessage> {
    val lastKnownId = getLastSyncedMessageId(conversationId)

    return try {
        val newMessages = messageApi.listMessages(
            agentId = agentId,
            conversationId = conversationId,
            after = lastKnownId,  // Letta API supports cursor-based pagination
            limit = 50,
            order = "asc",  // Get oldest-first for proper ordering
        ).toAppMessages()

        if (newMessages.isNotEmpty()) {
            // Merge into cache
            mergeMessagesIntoCache(conversationId, newMessages)
            // Update sync marker
            newMessages.lastOrNull()?.id?.let { 
                setLastSyncedMessageId(conversationId, it) 
            }
        }

        newMessages
    } catch (e: Exception) {
        emptyList()
    }
}
```

## Letta API Check

Verify `after` parameter is supported in the messages list endpoint. If not, use timestamp-based filtering.

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] `checkForNewMessages` implemented
- [ ] Uses `after` cursor or timestamp filter
- [ ] Merges new messages into cache
- [ ] Updates sync marker
- [ ] Returns empty list on error (silent fail for background sync)

## Problem

Currently `fetchMessages` always fetches the latest N messages. To detect new messages from other clients, we need to know what we already have.

## Solution

Add tracking of the last known message ID or timestamp per conversation:

```kotlin
// MessageRepository.kt
private val _lastSyncedMessageId = MutableStateFlow<Map<String, String>>(emptyMap())

fun getLastSyncedMessageId(conversationId: String): String? =
    _lastSyncedMessageId.value[conversationId]

fun setLastSyncedMessageId(conversationId: String, messageId: String) {
    _lastSyncedMessageId.update { it + (conversationId to messageId) }
}
```

Update `fetchMessages` to track:
```kotlin
suspend fun fetchMessages(...): List<AppMessage> {
    // ... existing fetch logic ...

    // Track last message for sync
    appMessages.lastOrNull()?.id?.let { lastId ->
        setLastSyncedMessageId(conversationId, lastId)
    }

    return appMessages
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] `_lastSyncedMessageId` map added to MessageRepository
- [ ] Updated after each successful fetch
- [ ] Getter method for polling to use
- [ ] Cleared when conversation changes or cache cleared

